<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911111-0085</DOCNO><DOCID>911111-0085.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- Fiat S.p.A:   Investment for Car Division   Over 10 Years Is Described</HL><DATE>11/11/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   FIA</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>AUTOMOBILES (AUT)</IN><RE>EUROPE (EU)ITALY (ITA)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   Fiat S.p.A., Italy's largest private-sector industrialcompany, plans to invest 40 trillion lire ($32.49 billion)during the next 10 years in its core car division, anindividual familiar with the company's plans said Friday.   The individual, who declined to be identified, said thatGiovanni Agnelli, chairman, told a group of more than 1,000managers of Fiat Auto S.p.A., the group's car-manufacturingsubsidiary, that the unit &quot;will remain the group's corebusiness.&quot; Fiat has interests that include retail, insurance,trucks, parts, financial services and civil engineering.</LP><TEXT>   The individual said Mr. Agnelli told the managers thatFiat is ready to face what he sees as a future madeundoubtedly difficult by increasing competition in the globalcar market. Fiat plans to develop a total of 18 models duringthe next decade for its three main brands, Fiat, Lancia andAlfa Romeo, the individual said.   The investments will be &quot;mostly self-financed&quot; from cashflow, which the company can afford because of its high levelof liquidity, the individual said. He said Fiat Auto hasfinancial liquidity of close to nine trillion lire ($7.3billion).</TEXT></DOC>